data.content:
This is a well-documented **C# 14 breaking change** related to new span overload resolution rules.

## What happened

In C# 14, `Span<T>` and `ReadOnlySpan<T>` overloads now participate in type inference and extension method resolution. When you write `array.Contains(num)` on an `int[]`, the compiler now binds to **`MemoryExtensions.Contains`** (which takes a `Span<T>`) instead of **`Enumerable.Contains`** (which takes `IEnumerable<T>`).

`MemoryExtensions.Contains` **cannot be represented in an expression tree**, so it throws at runtime.

## How to fix

Cast the array to `IEnumerable<T>`, use `.AsEnumerable()`, or call `Enumerable.Contains` explicitly:

```csharp
// Option 1: Cast
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 3: Explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

All three force the compiler to bind to `Enumerable.Contains`, which is representable in expression trees. The same pattern applies to `.Reverse()` on arrays (now binds to the in-place `MemoryExtensions.Reverse`).
